TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Medium and the Message: The Adaptive Use of Communication Media in Dyadic Influence
AU  - Barry, Bruce
AU  - Fulmer, Ingrid Smithey
Y1  - 2004/04/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2004.12736093
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2004.12736093
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 272
EP  - 292
VL  - 29
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We articulate a dynamic theory of media adaptation in dyadic influence. We identify key underlying attributes of media and discuss how individuals enact and regulate these features to use media adaptively within influence situations. Our model and propositions account for (1) the ways that attributes of communication media affect how influence-seeking behavior is generated and perceived and (2) the strategic adaptations of media that parties to organization-based influence attempts make.
AB  - We articulate a dynamic theory of media adaptation in dyadic influence. We identify key underlying attributes of media and discuss how individuals enact and regulate these features to use media adaptively within influence situations. Our model and propositions account for (1) the ways that attributes of communication media affect how influence-seeking behavior is generated and perceived and (2) the strategic adaptations of media that parties to organization-based influence attempts make.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2004.12736093
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2004.12736093
Y2  - 2026/04/24
